column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/93.0.4577.63 Safari/537.36 Edg/93.0.961.38
column137: Because I know how it feels and looks to write a number, I can see/imagine where the human started to write the number and where he finished (picked up his pen). For example, there were a couple questions where the symbol clearly looked like a 7 to me but the program labeled it a 2. The reason I considered it a 7 instead of a 2 is because people usually lift the pen to cross the 7 in the middle so there is no connection between the bottom of the 7 and the start of the line that crosses it in the middle. The program probably wouldn't have considered that  and instead analyzed similarities on looks alone.
column220: Maybe have even more human labelers with different writing styles teach the program their style of writing. If the program was able to see how one would write a number from beginning to end then I think it would almost always be able to recognize symbols.
